## 7. Scarcity: A Finite Supply of Premium Names

Scarcity is baked into the DNA of premium domain names. Unlike content or software, you cannot create more two-letter .ai domains. The supply is fixed, and as demand grows, prices rise.

### The Math of Scarcity

Consider the numbers:

- **Two-letter combinations (letters only):** 676 possible domains (26 x 26)
- **Two-character combinations (letters + digits):** 1,296 possible domains (36 x 36)
- **Single common English dictionary words:** Roughly 3,000 to 5,000 that would make good domain names
- **Single-syllable action verbs:** Maybe 200 to 300

Every time one of these domains sells and goes into active use by a company, it effectively leaves the resale market. The buyer is not flipping it. They are building on it. That further constricts supply.

### Increasing Demand, Fixed Supply

The AI industry is growing exponentially. According to Statista, the global AI market is projected to reach over $300 billion by 2026. Every new AI startup needs a domain name, and .ai is the most natural choice. With thousands of new AI companies launching every year, demand for quality .ai domains is accelerating while supply remains fixed.

This supply and demand imbalance is the fundamental driver behind rising .ai domain prices. In 2019, hp.ai selling for $565,000 was the record-setter for two-letter .ai domains. Today, that same domain would likely command significantly more.

### The "Land Grab" Analogy

Think of premium .ai domains like beachfront property. They are not making more coastline. Early buyers who secured prime locations at lower prices are now sitting on appreciating assets. The best names were registered years ago, and acquiring them now means paying aftermarket premiums.

This scarcity effect is most pronounced for:

- Two-character .ai domains (only 1,296 exist)
- Single dictionary word .ai domains (finite set of common words)
- Exact-match industry terms (only one "data.ai," only one "chat.ai")

